Tourette's syndrome is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by the presence of motor and/or vocal tics, which are sudden, repetitive, and involuntary movements or sounds. The symptoms of Tourette's syndrome can vary in severity and may include:

* Motor tics: These are sudden, involuntary movements of the face, head, neck, or other parts of the body. Examples of motor tics include:
	+ Eye blinking or rolling
	+ Facial grimacing or contortions
	+ Neck twisting or jerking
	+ Shoulder shrugging or arm jerking
	+ Leg or foot movements
* Vocal tics: These are sudden, involuntary sounds or words that are spoken. Examples of vocal tics include:
	+ Simple sounds, such as 'ah' or 'oh'
	+ Complex sounds, such as words or phrases
	+ Repeating words or phrases
	+ Making sounds, such as grunting or snorting

If you are concerned that you or someone you know may have Tourette's syndrome, it is important to consult with a qualified healthcare professional for a proper evaluation and diagnosis.

I'm glad you asked! I'd be happy to suggest some activities that may be helpful for you as a person with reading difficulties. Here are some ideas:

1. Audiobooks: Listening to audiobooks is an excellent way to enjoy stories and learn new things without relying on reading. You can find audiobooks at your local library or purchase them online.
2. E-books with text-to-speech: Many e-books come with text-to-speech features that can read the text aloud to you. This can be a helpful tool for those with reading difficulties.
3. Large print books: Large print books can make reading easier for those with visual impairments or reading difficulties. You can find large print books at your local library or bookstore.
4. Graphic novels and comics: Graphic novels and comics can be a great way to enjoy stories through visuals and fewer words. They can be an excellent alternative to traditional novels for those with reading difficulties.
5. Listening to podcasts: Podcasts can be an excellent way to learn new things and stay informed on various topics. Many podcasts are available for free and cover a wide range of subjects.
6. Joining a book club: Joining a book club can be a fun and social way to engage with literature. You can find book clubs in your local community or online.
7. Using assistive technology: There are many assistive technologies available that can help make reading easier for those with reading difficulties. For example, text-to-speech software, screen readers, and magnifiers can all be helpful tools.
8. Reading aloud with a friend or family member: Reading aloud with someone else can be a helpful way to improve reading skills and build confidence. You can also take turns reading to each other, which can make the experience more enjoyable.
9. Watching movies or TV shows based on books: Watching movies or TV shows based on books can be a great way to experience the story without having to read the entire book. It can also be a helpful way to improve comprehension and vocabulary.
10. Practicing reading regularly: Finally, it's important to remember that practice makes perfect. Regularly practicing reading, even if it's just for a few minutes each day, can help improve reading skills over time.
